Social network sites are becoming essential to how people experience news. For this project we developed supervised machine learning models to predict the popularity of news for the topics Obama, Economy, Palestine and Microsoft on the following social networks: Facebook, Google+ and LinkedIn.

The dataset we used can be found here.

  • IDLink is a unique number that represents the news article.
  • Title is the article's title.
  • Headline is the article's headline.
  • Source is the name of the news outlet that published the article.
  • Topic is the topic of the article. Can be one of the following: Obama, Economy, Palestine and Microsoft.
  • PublishDate is the date and time of the article's publication.
  • SentimentTitle is a sentiment score for the article's title. Ranges from -1 (negative) to +1 (positive).
  • SentimentHeadline is a sentiment score for the article's headline. Ranges from -1 (negative) to +1 (positive).
  • Facebook is the number of times the news was shared on Facebook.
  • GooglePlus is the number of times the news was shared on GooglePlus.
  • LinkedIn is the number of times the news was shared on LinkedIn.

Preprocess data.¶

In [5]:
# Encode topic feature so it can used with sk-learn models.
topic_encoder = LabelEncoder()
topic_encoder.fit(data['Topic'].astype(str))
data['Topic'] = topic_encoder.transform(data['Topic'].astype(str))

# Extract PublishDay and PublishHour from PublishDate.
data['PublishDay'] = data['PublishDate'].astype(str).apply(lambda x: parse(x).weekday())
data['PublishHour'] = data['PublishDate'].astype(str).apply(lambda x: parse(x).hour)
data['_PublishHour'] = data['PublishHour']; # Save non-normalized PublishHour for later.

# Normalize PublishDay and PublishHour to interval [0,1].
min_max_scaler = MinMaxScaler()
data[['PublishDay']] = min_max_scaler.fit_transform(data[['PublishDay']].astype(float))
data[['PublishHour']] = min_max_scaler.fit_transform(data[['PublishHour']].astype(float))

X = data[FEATURES]  # Input variables.
Y = data[RESPONSES] # Output variables. A ML model will be developed for each.

Helper Functions.¶

In [6]:
# Returns the training set and testing set for a given social network.
# This is required because not all news are published in all of them.
def get_sets(social_network): 
    sn_y_train = Y_train[Y_train[social_network] >= 0]
    sn_X_train = X_train[X_train.index.isin(sn_y_train.index)].dropna()
    sn_y_test = Y_test[Y_test[social_network] >= 0]
    sn_X_test = X_test[X_test.index.isin(sn_y_test.index)].dropna()
    return sn_X_train, sn_y_train[social_network], sn_X_test, sn_y_test[social_network]

Building the ML models.¶


In this section we proceed to train and test several Machine Learning models using popular regression algorithms.

The metrics we will be using to evaluate those models are the Root Mean Square Error (RMSE), which is the square root of the mean of the squared errors, and the Coefficient of Determination (R), which measures how well a model explains the variance in the data.

Linear and Polynomial Regression.¶

Polynomial Regression is a form of regression analysis in which the relationship between the independent variables X and the dependent variable y is modeled as an nth degree polynomial in x.

Linear regression can be thought as a particular case of Polynomial Regression in which the polynomial degree n is 1.

In [150]:
for degree in range(1,5):
    print('\r')
    if(degree == 1):
        print("Linear regression.")
    else:
        print("Polynomial regression, degree = {}.".format(degree))
    for social_network in RESPONSES: 
        sn_X_train, sn_y_train, sn_X_test, sn_y_test = get_sets(social_network)
        lr_model = make_pipeline(PolynomialFeatures(degree), LinearRegression())
        lr_model.fit(sn_X_train, sn_y_train)
        sn_y_pred = lr_model.predict(sn_X_test)
        print("[{}] RMSE: {}".format(social_network, np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(sn_y_test, sn_y_pred))))
        print("[{}] R^2: {}".format(social_network, metrics.r2_score(sn_y_test, sn_y_pred)))

K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN).¶

The goal of KNN is to predict a new observation response by looking up the most similar K train test samples.

It can be used in regression and classification problems.

In [29]:
# Test with k from 1 to 50
k_range = list(range(1, 51))

k_rmse = {}
k_k2 = {}
for social_network in RESPONSES: 
    k_rmse[social_network] = []
    k_k2[social_network] = []
    for k in k_range:
        knn = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=k)
        sn_X_train, sn_y_train, sn_X_test, sn_y_test = get_sets(social_network)
        knn.fit(sn_X_train, sn_y_train)
        y_pred = knn.predict(sn_X_test)
        k_rmse[social_network].append(np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(sn_y_test, y_pred)))
        k_k2[social_network].append(metrics.r2_score(sn_y_test, y_pred))

# Display plots.
sns.set_style("darkgrid")
for social_network in RESPONSES:
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(k_range, k_rmse[social_network], label=social_network, color = COLORS[social_network])
    plt.xlabel('Value of K for KNN')
    plt.ylabel('Root Mean Square Error')
    plt.legend()
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(k_range, k_k2[social_network], label=social_network, color = COLORS[social_network])
    plt.xlabel('Value of K for KNN')
    plt.ylabel('R^2')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

Support-Vector Regression (SVR).¶

A SVR performs linear regression in higher dimensional space. Each data point in the training represents its own dimension. When the kernel is evaluated between a test point and a training point, the resulting value gives the coordinate to the test point in that dimension.

In [10]:
from sklearn.svm import SVR 

svr_model = SVR(gamma=.1, C=100, epsilon=.1)
for social_network in RESPONSES: 
        sn_X_train, sn_y_train, sn_X_test, sn_y_test = get_sets(social_network)
        svr_model.fit(sn_X_train, sn_y_train)
        sn_y_pred = svr_model.predict(sn_X_test)
        sn_rmse = np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(sn_y_test, sn_y_pred))
        sn_r2 = metrics.r2_score(sn_y_test, sn_y_pred)
        print("[{}] RMSE: {} - R^2: {}".format(social_network, sn_rmse, sn_r2))

Neural Network.¶

Artificial neural network are computational networks based on biological neural networks. These models aim to replicate the complex network of neurons in our brains.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.neural_network import MLPRegressor


for social_network in RESPONSES: 
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
    sn_X_train, sn_y_train, sn_X_test, sn_y_test = get_sets(social_network)

    INNER_LAYERS = [
        (10),
        (100),
        (10, 10),
        (100, 100),
        (10, 10, 10),
        (100, 100, 100),
        (100, 50, 25),
        (25, 50, 100)
    ]

    N_TRAIN_SAMPLES = sn_X_train.shape[0]
    N_EPOCHS = 100
    N_EPOCHS_RANGE = list(range(1, N_EPOCHS))
    N_BATCH = sn_X_train.shape[0]
    scores_rmse = {}
    scores_r2 = {}

    for layers_size in INNER_LAYERS:
        nn_model = MLPRegressor(activation='relu',solver='adam', early_stopping=False, warm_start=True, max_iter=2000)
        epoch = 1
        scores_rmse[layers_size] = []
        scores_r2[layers_size] = []
        while epoch < N_EPOCHS:
            nn_model.partial_fit(sn_X_train, sn_y_train)

            # SCORE TEST
            y_pred = nn_model.predict(sn_X_test)
            scores_rmse[layers_size].append(np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(sn_y_test, y_pred)))
            scores_r2[layers_size].append(metrics.r2_score(sn_y_test, y_pred))

            epoch += 1
       
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    for layers_size in INNER_LAYERS:     
        plt.plot(N_EPOCHS_RANGE, scores_rmse[layers_size], label=str(layers_size))
    plt.ylabel('[{}] Root Mean Squared Error'.format(social_network))
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.legend()
    
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    for layers_size in INNER_LAYERS:     
        plt.plot(N_EPOCHS_RANGE, scores_r2[layers_size], label=str(layers_size))
    plt.ylabel('[{}] R^2'.format(social_network))
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
